Effect spaces.

The effect space builder lets you place zones on a map that apply audio effects to all sounds within their boundaries. When a sound source enters an effect zone, the effect is applied automatically. When it leaves, the effect is cleared.

To place an effect space, open the builder menu and select effect space. You will be prompted for the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of the zone, a unique ID for the zone, and the effect type. Depending on the effect type, a set of sliders will appear to tune the parameters. You can press space to preview how the effect sounds on the current surface before saving.

Multiple effect zones of different types can overlap. Each effect type is tracked independently, so a zone can apply reverb and lowpass at the same time if two overlapping zones of those types cover the same area.

Effect Overview

The following is a quick summary of every effect type and its parameters.

Echo: dry mix, wet mix, feedback, delay (ms).
Reverb: dry mix, wet mix, room size, damping, width.
Lowpass: frequency (hz), bandwidth (oct), quality.
Highpass: frequency (hz), bandwidth (oct), quality.
Chorus: dry mix, wet mix, feedback, min sweep (ms), max sweep (ms), rate (ms/s).
Distortion: drive, dry mix, wet mix, feedback, volume.
Phaser: dry mix, wet mix, rate (hz), depth, feedback, phase (deg).
Flanger: dry mix, wet mix, feedback, min delay (ms), max delay (ms), rate (hz).

Individual Effect Reference

Echo

Repeats the sound after a short delay, creating the impression of a large open space such as a canyon, mountain range, or empty warehouse. The delay parameter controls how far away the reflection feels, and feedback controls how many times the echo repeats before dying out.

dry mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the original unprocessed signal. Lower values push the sound further into the distance.
wet mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the echoed signal mixed in on top of the original.
feedback (min 0, mid 50, max 100): How much of the echo feeds back into itself. Low values produce a single clean repeat. High values produce many repeats that fade out slowly, simulating a very reflective environment.
delay (min 0, mid 500, max 1000 ms): How long in milliseconds before the first echo is heard. Short delays of around 100 to 200 ms feel like a small room. Long delays of 500 ms or more feel like a wide open outdoor space.

Reverb

Simulates the natural ambience of an enclosed space by blending many short reflections together into a continuous tail. Unlike echo, reverb does not produce distinct repeats. Instead it creates a sense of the room itself. This is the most natural-sounding effect for indoor environments.

dry mix (min 0, mid 50, max 100): The volume of the original unprocessed signal.
wet mix (min 0, mid 150, max 300): The volume of the reverb tail mixed in with the original signal. Reverb wet mix goes higher than other effects to allow the reverb to fully wash over the sound.
room size (min 0, mid 50, max 100): Controls how large the simulated space feels. Low values feel like a small closet or bathroom. High values feel like a cathedral or cavern.
damping (min 0, mid 50, max 100): Controls how much high frequencies are absorbed by the walls. Low values produce a bright, reflective space like a tiled room. High values produce a soft, absorptive space like a carpeted room or forest.
width (min 0, mid 50, max 100): The stereo spread of the reverb tail. Low values keep the reverb centered. High values spread it wide across both ears.

Lowpass

Removes high frequencies from sounds, letting only low frequencies pass through. The result is a muffled, dark quality that makes sounds feel distant, blocked, or submerged. This is one of the most useful effects for environmental storytelling.

frequency (min 0, mid 11000, max 22000 hz): The cutoff point. Frequencies above this value are reduced. Lower values produce a more extreme muffle effect. A value around 500 hz sounds heavily muffled as if behind a thick wall. A value around 3000 hz sounds slightly dulled as if in a foggy outdoor area.
bandwidth (min 0, mid 500, max 1000 oct): Controls how gradually the cutoff takes effect. Low values produce a very gentle slope. High values produce a sharper, more defined cutoff.
quality (min 0, mid 50, max 100): Adds a slight resonance boost right at the cutoff frequency. Low values produce a flat, natural filter. Higher values add a subtle coloration at the cutoff point.

Highpass

Removes low frequencies from sounds, letting only high frequencies pass through. The result is a thin, hollow quality that makes sounds feel distant, electronic, or filtered. The opposite of lowpass.

frequency (min 0, mid 11000, max 22000 hz): The cutoff point. Frequencies below this value are reduced. Higher values produce a more extreme thinning effect. A value around 500 hz removes the bass from a sound. A value around 3000 hz produces a very thin, telephone-like quality.
bandwidth (min 0, mid 500, max 1000 oct): Controls how gradually the cutoff takes effect. Low values produce a gentle slope. High values produce a sharper cutoff.
quality (min 0, mid 50, max 100): Adds a slight resonance boost right at the cutoff frequency. Low values produce a flat, natural filter. Higher values add a subtle coloration at the cutoff point.

Chorus

Layers multiple slightly detuned and delayed copies of the sound on top of each other, creating a thick, shimmering, wide quality. Commonly heard on guitars and vocals in music. In a game context it is well suited to magical zones, underwater areas, or dreamlike environments.

dry mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the original unprocessed signal.
wet mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the chorused signal mixed in.
feedback (min 0, mid 50, max 100): How much of the chorus signal feeds back into itself. Low values produce a subtle shimmer. High values produce a denser, more swirling effect.
min sweep (min 0, mid 3000, max 6000 ms): The shortest point of the modulation cycle. This is the minimum delay time the effect oscillates down to.
max sweep (min 0, mid 3000, max 6000 ms): The longest point of the modulation cycle. This is the maximum delay time the effect oscillates up to. A larger gap between min and max sweep produces a wider, more dramatic sweep.
rate (min 0, mid 500, max 1000 ms/s): How fast the sweep oscillates between the min and max values. Lower values produce a slow, gentle undulation. Higher values produce a faster, more obvious wobble.

Distortion

Clips and saturates the audio signal, adding harmonic content and a gritty, aggressive texture. Well suited to industrial zones, areas with broken machinery, electrical hazards, or any environment that should feel harsh and hostile.

drive (min 0, mid 250, max 500): How hard the signal is pushed into clipping. Low values add a mild warmth. High values produce heavy, grinding distortion.
dry mix (min 0, mid 250, max 500): The volume of the original unprocessed signal.
wet mix (min 0, mid 250, max 500): The volume of the distorted signal mixed in.
feedback (min 0, mid 50, max 100): Feeds the distorted signal back into itself for more extreme, self-reinforcing distortion. High values can produce a very aggressive, unstable sound.
volume (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The output level after distortion is applied. Because distortion tends to make signals louder, this can be used to bring the overall level back down after increasing drive.

Phaser

Splits the audio signal and applies a continuously sweeping all-pass filter to one copy before mixing it back with the original. The two copies interact to cancel and reinforce different frequencies as the sweep moves, producing a swirling, jet-like whoosh. Best used for supernatural zones, portals, psychedelic environments, or any area that should feel disorienting or otherworldly.

dry mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the original unprocessed signal.
wet mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the phased signal mixed in.
rate (min 0, mid 5, max 10 hz): How fast the phase sweep oscillates. Low values of 0 to 1 hz produce a slow, creeping movement. Values around 3 to 5 hz produce a more obvious swirl. Higher values produce a rapid fluttering effect.
depth (min 0, mid 50, max 100): How wide the sweep range is. Low values produce a subtle effect. High values produce a more dramatic, wide-ranging sweep.
feedback (min 0, mid 50, max 100): Feeds the phased signal back into itself, making the effect sharper and more pronounced. High values produce a more metallic, resonant quality.
phase (min 0, mid 180, max 360 deg): The starting angle of the sweep in degrees. This controls where in the cycle the effect begins when the sound enters the zone. For most uses the default of 180 degrees works well.

Flanger

Similar to phaser, but instead of an all-pass filter it uses a very short variable delay that sweeps back and forth, producing a comb-filter effect. The result is a hollow, metallic, jet-engine-like sweep. Flanging is most recognizable from classic science fiction sound design and electric guitar processing. Runs on the same engine code as chorus but with much shorter delay times, which is what gives it its distinct character. For a true flanger sound, keep both the min and max delay values low, between 1 and 10 milliseconds.

dry mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the original unprocessed signal.
wet mix (min 0, mid 100, max 200): The volume of the flanged signal mixed in.
feedback (min 0, mid 50, max 100): Feeds the flanged signal back into itself, producing a more hollow and metallic quality. High values produce the most extreme, resonant flanger character.
min delay (min 0, mid 10, max 20 ms): The shortest delay time in the sweep. Keep this low for a true flanger effect. Values between 0 and 5 ms are typical.
max delay (min 0, mid 10, max 20 ms): The longest delay time in the sweep. Keep this low for a true flanger effect. Values between 5 and 10 ms are typical. A larger gap between min and max delay produces a wider sweep.
rate (min 0, mid 5, max 10 hz): How fast the delay sweeps between the min and max values. Low values of around 0.1 to 0.5 hz produce a slow, jet-like sweep. Higher values produce a faster, more mechanical wobble.
